{{Infobox Artwork | image_file= [[File:The_Soothsayer's_Recompense_de_Chirico.jpg|200px]] | backcolor= | painting_alignment= | image_size= | title=The Soothsayers Recompense | artist=[[Giorgio de Chirico]] | year=1913 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric= | width_metric= | height_imperial= 53 3/8 | width_imperial= 70 7/8 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] | museum=[[Philadelphia Museum of Art]] | accession = 1950 }} '''''The Soothsayers Recompense''''' is a 1913 painting by the Italian artist [[Giorgio de Chirico]].<ref name=Pritchard>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/squaring-the-ancient-and-the-modern-the-art-of-giorgio-de-chirico-9037478.html |title=Squaring the ancient and the modern: The art of Giorgio de Chirico |last=Pritchard |first=Claudia |date=4 January 2014 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |access-date=13 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=dorment>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/3588891/Secrets-and-lies-in-the-piazza.html |title=Secrets and lies in the piazza |last=Dorment |first=Richard |author-link=Richard Dorment |date=22 January 2003 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=13 March 2016 |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group Limited]]}}</ref> It is currently housed in the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]] as part of the permanent collection. It was accessioned in 1950 as one of the thousand items donated to the institution by [[Walter Conrad Arensberg|Walter and Louise Arensberg]].<ref name=phila>{{cite web |url=http://www.philamuseum.org/collections/permanent/51288.html |title=The Soothsayer's Recompense |date=1 January 2007 |work=[[The Philadelphia Museum of Art]] |access-date=13 March 2016}}</ref> The piece was created in France, through a process of "squaring-up" in which De Chirico drew a version of the piece divided into nine squares, and subsequently used this draft to quickly create the fleshed-out painting.<ref name=phila/><ref>{{cite journal |last=Gale |first=Matthew |date=1 April 1988 |title=The Uncertainty of the Painter: De Chirico in 1913 |journal=[[The Burlington Magazine]] |volume=130 |issue=1021 |pages=268–276 |jstor=883282 |publisher=Burlington Magazine Publications Ltd.}}</ref>
==Subject matter== The piece depicts an empty city square, a recurring motif in works by De Chirico.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Giorgio-de-Chirico#ref216264 |title=Giorgio de Chirico |author=The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica |date=30 June 2014 |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] |access-date=13 March 2016 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]}}</ref> It also features a locomotive in the background, another recurring motif also found in ''[[Le Rêve Transformé]]'' and ''[[Gare Montparnasse (The Melancholy of Departure)]]''.
The statue at the center of the painting is meant to represent [[Ariadne]],<ref name=dorment/> who was the daughter of Minos, King of Crete.<ref>{{cite book |author=Homer |author-link=Homer |title=[[Odyssey]] |others=11.320}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Hesiod |author-link=Hesiod |title=[[Theogony]] |others=947}}</ref> She assisted [[Theseus]] in his escape from the [[Labyrinth]], but he later abandoned her on the island of [[Naxos]]. Like the locomotive and empty square, Ariadne appears in other paintings by De Chirico.
==Display history== ''The Soothsayer's Recompense'' is currently owned by the Philadelphia Museum of Art, and was first shown there in 1954.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Kimball |first=Fiske |year=1954 |title=Opening of the Louise and Walter Arensberg Collection. The "Modern Museum" of the Philadelphia Museum of Art |journal=The Philadelphia Museum Bulletin |volume=50 |issue=243 |pages=3–15 |jstor=3794892 |publisher=[[Philadelphia Museum of Art]] |doi=10.2307/3794892}}</ref> It originally hung in the home of the Arensberg family, where it inspired [[Philip Guston]] to become a painter.<ref name=xtra>{{cite journal |url=http://x-traonline.org/article/the-soothsayers-recompense/ |title=The Soothsayer’s Recompense |last=Allen |first=Tom |date=1 June 2007 |work=X•Tra |access-date=13 March 2016 |volume=9 |issue=4}}</ref> Since being accessioned by its current owner, it has been shown elsewhere, including twice at the [[Estorick Collection of Modern Italian Art]] in 2003 and again in 2014, and at the [[Santa Monica Museum of Art]] in 2007.<ref name=Pritchard/><ref name=dorment/><ref name=xtra/>
